\description{
For a fitted \code{\link[=fetwfe]{fetwfe()}} / \code{\link[=etwfe]{etwfe()}} / \code{\link[=betwfe]{betwfe()}} object, computes the
closed-form conditional average treatment effect on the treated at a
user-supplied covariate vector \code{x}, for every cohort \code{r} and post-
treatment time \code{t} the model estimated:

\deqn{\hat\tau_{\mathrm{CATT}}(r, t, x) = \hat\tau_{rt} +
    (x - \bar X_r)^\top \hat\rho_{rt}}

(paper Eq. \code{catt.t.r.est}). Asymptotic standard errors and Wald
confidence intervals follow Theorem \code{te.asym.norm.thm.gen.cond}(a)
from the methodology paper (Eq. \code{v.n.r.t.catt.const}).

Output is a long-form data frame with one row per
\verb{(newdata_row x cohort x post-treatment time)} combination. When
\code{newdata = NULL} (the default), predictions are computed at each
cohort's sample-mean covariate vector \eqn{\bar X_r}, so the
\verb{(x - \\bar X_r)^\\top \\hat\\rho_\{rt\}} term vanishes and the
\code{estimate} column reduces to \eqn{\hat\tau_{rt}}.
}
\details{
The variance formula (paper Eq. \code{v.n.r.t.catt.const}) decomposes into
two components for a single-\verb{(r, t, x)} prediction:
\enumerate{
\item \strong{Regression-coefficient variance.} The joint sampling
uncertainty in \eqn{(\hat\tau_{rt}, \hat\rho_{rt})} carried
through the selected-features Gram inverse
\eqn{\hat\Sigma((Z D_N^{-1})_{\cdot, \hat S})^{-1}} and the
relevant rows of \eqn{D_N^{-1}} (the row corresponding to
\eqn{\tau_{rt}} and the \code{d} rows corresponding to \eqn{\rho_{rt}}),
scaled by \eqn{(x - \bar X_r)} on the \eqn{\rho} block.
\item \strong{Cohort-mean variance.} Additional \eqn{O_p(N^{-1/2})} noise
from estimating \eqn{\bar X_r} with the sample mean over the
\eqn{N_r} units in cohort \code{r}. This term equals
\eqn{\hat\rho_{rt}^\top \widehat{\mathrm{Cov}}(X_i \mid W_i = r)
       \hat\rho_{rt} / N_r}.
}

Both components are nonnegative in expectation; floating-point-tiny
negatives from numerical cancellation are floored to zero via the
same diagnostic helper used for the cluster-robust SE machinery.

When \code{newdata = NULL}, the \verb{(x - \\bar X_r)^\\top \\hat\\rho_\{rt\}} term
vanishes by construction, and the regression-variance component
collapses to the same expression the package already reports for the
per-\verb{(r, t)} cohort treatment effect (component (1)). The
cohort-mean variance term remains, reflecting the fact that even at
\eqn{x = \bar X_r}, the population \eqn{\bar X_r} is estimated.

Note on the variance formula. The paper's Theorem
\code{te.asym.norm.thm.gen.cond}(a) (Eq. \code{v.n.r.t.catt.const}) gives the
asymptotically exact variance \eqn{v_{\mathrm{reg}} + v_{\mathrm{mean}}}
under the sample-split assumption: one panel for the cohort means
\eqn{\bar X_r}, an independent panel for \eqn{\hat\tau_{rt}} and
\eqn{\hat\rho_{rt}}. In practice this is the setting where the user
supplies \code{indep_counts} at fit time. When \code{indep_counts} is not
supplied, both variance components are estimated from the same panel
and the formula does not capture the covariance between
\eqn{(\bar X_r - \mu_r)} and \eqn{(\hat\rho_{rt} - \rho_{rt})};
\code{predict()} then falls back to the Cauchy-Schwarz conservative upper
bound \eqn{(\sqrt{v_{\mathrm{reg}}} + \sqrt{v_{\mathrm{mean}}})^2}.
This mirrors the overall-ATT SE convention the package already uses
for \code{att_se} -- asymptotically exact when \code{indep_counts} is supplied,
conservative otherwise. At \eqn{x = \bar X_r} (the default
\code{newdata = NULL}), the cross-term issue does not arise
(\eqn{x - \bar X_r = 0}) and the conservative formula coincides
numerically with the exact one.
